<td><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">ŋ</span></td>
<td><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">ɡʱ</span></td>
<td><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">ɠ</span></td>
<td><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">ɡ</span></td>
<td><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">kʰ</span></td>
<td><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">k</span></td>
</tr>
</table>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Sindhi_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Devanagari Script">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Devanagari_Script">Devanagari Script</span></h3>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Devanagari" title="Devanagari">Devanagari</a> script is also used to write Sindhi. A modern version was introduced by the government of India in 1948; however, it did not gain full acceptance, so both the Sindhi-Arabic and <a href="/wiki/Devanagari" title="Devanagari">Devanagari</a> scripts are used. In <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a> a person may write a <a href="/wiki/Sindhi" title="Sindhi">Sindhi</a> language paper for a Civil Services Examination in either script <a href="http://www.lmp.ucla.edu/Profile.aspx?menu=004&amp;LangID=201" class="external autonumber" rel="nofollow">[1]</a>. <a href="/wiki/Diacritic" title="Diacritic">Diacritical</a> bars below the letter are used to mark implosive consonants, and <a href="/wiki/Dot_(diacritic)" title="Dot (diacritic)">dots</a> called <i><a href="/wiki/Nukta" title="Nukta">nukta</a></i> are used to form other additional consonants.</p>
