<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6">^</a></b> The IPA <i>Handbook uses the symbols <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">c, cʰ, ɟ, ɟʱ</span>, but makes it clear this is simply tradition and that these are neither palatal nor stops, but "laminal post-alveolars with a relatively short release". Ladefoged &amp; Maddieson (1996:83) confirm a transcription of <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[t̠ɕ, t̠ɕʰ, d̠ʑ, d̠ʑʱ]</span> and further remarks that "<span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/ʄ/</span> is often a slightly creaky voiced palatal approximant" (caption of table 3.19).</i></li>
